{"title_page": "Joe Pesci", "text_new": "{{pp-pc}}\n{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Joe Pesci\n| image              = JoePesci-2009.jpg\n| alt                = A head shot of Pesci, unshaven, wearing dark sunglasses, hat, shirt, and leather jacket\n| caption            = Pesci in November 2009\n| birth_name         = Joseph Frank Pesci\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1943|2|9}}  \n| birth_place        = [[Newark, New Jersey]], U.S.\n| residence          = [[Lavallette, New Jersey]], U.S.\n| occupation         = Actor, musician<!--Please do not add \"comedian\" as it was for a very brief period early on in his career, which is not something he is known for.-->\n| years_active       = 1961\u20131999; 2006\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Claudia Haro]]|1988|1992|reason=divorced}}\n| partner            = [[Angie Everhart]] (2000\u20132008)\n| children           = 1\n}}\n\n'''Joseph Frank Pesci''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|p|\u025b|\u0283|i}} {{respell|PESH|ee}}, {{IPA-it|\u02c8pe\u0283\u02d0i}}; born February 9, 1943) is an American actor, comedian, and musician<!-\" as it was for a very brief period early on in his career, which is not something he is known for.-->. He is known for portraying tough, volatile characters in a variety of genres and for his collaborations with [[Robert De Niro]] and [[Martin Scorsese]] in the films ''[[Raging Bull]]'' (1980), ''[[Goodfellas]]'' (1990), ''[[Casino (1995 film)|Casino]]'' (1995), and ''[[The Irishman]]'' (2019). He also appeared in ''[[Once Upon a Time in America]]'' (1984), ''[[Moonwalker]]'' (1988), ''[[JFK (film)|JFK]]'' (1991), ''[[A Bronx Tale]]'' (1993), and ''[[The Good Shepherd (film)|The Good Shepherd]]'' (2006). His comedy roles include such films as ''[[Home Alone]]'' (1990), ''[[My Cousin Vinny]]'' (1992), ''[[Home Alone 2: Lost in New York]]'' (1992), and the [[Lethal Weapon (franchise)|''Lethal Weapon'' franchise]] (1989\u20131998).\n\nPesci won the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]] for his role as the psychopathic gangster [[Thomas DeSimone|Tommy DeVito]] in ''Goodfellas'' and received two other nominations in the same category for his portrayals of [[Joey LaMotta]] and [[Russell Bufalino]] in 1980's ''Raging Bull'' and in 2019's ''The Irishman'', respectively. He announced his retirement from acting in 1999, and has since appeared only occasionally in films. He is also a musician who recorded three studio albums, ''Little Joe Sure Can Sing!'' (1968), ''[[Vincent LaGuardia Gambini Sings Just for You]]'' (1998) and ''Pesci... Still Singing'' (2019).\n\n== Early life ==\nPesci was born on February 9, 1943, in [[Newark, New Jersey]]. His mother, Maria (Mesce), worked part-time as a barber, and his father, Angelo Pesci, was a [[forklift]] driver for [[General Motors]] and a bartender. He is of Italian descent, with origins in [[Turin]]<ref name=\"character\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/03/08/movies/film-joe-pesci-that-guy-is-some-kind-of-character.html |title=Joe Pesci? That Guy Is Some Kind of Character |first=Nancy |last=Harrison |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 8, 1992 |publisher=[[New York Times Company|NYTC]] |location=[[New York, NY|New York]] |issn=0362-4331 |accessdate=October 21, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151114195953/http://www.nytimes.com/1992/03/08/movies/film-joe-pesci-that-guy-is-some-kind-of-character.html |archive-date=November 14, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://celebritywonder.ugo.com/html/joepesci.html |title=Joe Pesci |work=celebritywonder |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110321114922/http://celebritywonder.ugo.com/html/joepesci.html |archivedate=March 21, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=MHJ1DQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=%22Italian+Americans:+The+History+and+Culture+of+a+People%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjS37SP-MjmAhXDK80KHd3VChIQ6AEwAHoECAAQAQ|title=Italian Americans: The History and Culture of a People|first=Eric|last=Martone|date=December 12, 2016|publisher=ABC-CLIO|via=Google Books}}</ref> and [[Aquilonia, Campania|Aquilonia]] in [[province of Avellino]].<ref>{{cite news |last1= Aspesi|first1=Natalia|author-link1= |last2= |first2= |author-link2= |last3= |first3= |author-link3= |last4= |first4= |author-link4= |last5= |first5= |author-link5= |display-authors= |author-mask= |name-list-format= |last-author-amp= |date= |year= |orig-year= |title=Piccolo e nero mezzo italiano Pesci \u00e8 la star |script-title= |trans-title= |url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/1992/09/04/piccolo-nero-mezzo-italiano-pesci-la.html |url-status= |editor1-last= |editor1-first= |editor1-link= |editor2-last= |editor2-first= |editor2-link= |editor3-last= |editor3-first= |editor3-link= |editor4-last= |editor4-first= |editor4-link= |editor5-last= |editor5-first= |editor5-link= |display-editors= |department= |work=la Repubblica |type= |series= |language=Italian |volume= |issue= |others= |edition= |location= Rome|publisher=GEDI Gruppo Editoriale |publication-date=September 4, 1992 |agency= |page= |pages= |at= |nopp= |arxiv= |asin= |bibcode= |doi= |doi-broken-date= |isbn= |issn= |jfm= |jstor= |lccn= |mr= |oclc= |ol= |osti= |pmc= |pmid= |rfc= |ssrn= |zbl= |id= |archive-url= |archive-date= |access-date=February 9, 2020 |via= |registration= |lay-url= |lay-source= |lay-date= |quote= |postscript= |ref= }}</ref> Pesci was raised in [[Belleville, New Jersey]], and graduated from [[Belleville High School (New Jersey)|Belleville High School]]. By the time Pesci was five years old, he was appearing in plays in New York.<ref name=\"character\" /> At age 10, he was a regular on a television variety show called ''Startime Kids'', which also featured [[Connie Francis]].<ref name=\"character\" />\n\nAs a teenager, Pesci was friends with singers [[Frankie Valli]] (who is nine years his senior) and [[Tommy DeVito (musician)|Tommy DeVito]] (who is 15 years his senior), and in 1959, at age 16, he helped introduce them to singer and songwriter [[Bob Gaudio]], which led to the formation of the band [[The Four Seasons (band)|the Four Seasons]].<ref name=\"history vs hollywood\">{{cite web |url=http://www.historyvshollywood.com/reelfaces/jersey-boys/ |title=Jersey Boys Movie vs True Story \u2013 Real Frankie Valli, Tommy DeVito |work=HistoryvsHollywood.com |accessdate=October 21, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150627204444/http://www.historyvshollywood.com/reelfaces/jersey-boys/ |archivedate=June 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n=== Early career ===\nIn the 1960s, Pesci began working as a barber, following in his mother's footsteps. At the same time, he tried to start a musical career, playing guitar with several bands, including [[Joey Dee and the Starliters]] who introduced the \"[[Peppermint Twist]]\" record, dance, and Peppermint Lounge in New York City.\n\nIn 1968, he released his debut album ''Little Joe Sure Can Sing!'' (billed as ''Joe Ritchie''), on which he sang covers of contemporary pop hits.<ref name=\"yahoo\">{{cite web |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/person/joe-pesci/biography.html |title=Joe Pesci biography |work=[[Yahoo! Movies]] |access-date=January 14, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315102847/https://movies.yahoo.com/person/joe-pesci/biography.html |archive-date=March 15, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPesci later joined [[Frank Vincent]] as a [[comedy duo]], performing as \"Vincent and Pesci\" from 1970 to 1976. Their act coupled [[Abbott and Costello]]-inspired double act antics with [[Don Rickles]]-style [[insult comedy]], which proved popular with crowds. During this time, both men developed a strong professional and personal friendship with one another.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lewine |first1=Edward |title=Frank Vincent's Two-Limo Night |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/18/nyregion/frank-vincent-s-two-limo-night.html |website=[[New York Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Eidelstein |first1=Eric |title=The Mysterious Disappearing Act of Joe Pesci |url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2015/09/where-are-you-joe-pesci |website=[[Complex (magazine)]]}}</ref> In 1975, they appeared in the Broadway show ''The New Vaudevillians'', which only lasted one week.<ref name=\"yahoo\" />\n\nThe first film Pesci starred in was the 1976 [[Low-budget film|low-budget]] [[crime film]] ''[[The Death Collector]]'' alongside Frank Vincent. After the film Pesci returned to The Bronx and lived above Amici's Restaurant, where he was an employee.<ref name=\"yahoo\" />\n\n=== Acting career ===\nIn 1979, Pesci received a telephone call from [[Martin Scorsese]] and Robert De Niro, who were impressed with his performance in ''The Death Collector'' and asked him to co-star in Scorsese's ''[[Raging Bull]]'' as [[Joey LaMotta]]. During the course of filming, Pesci broke one of his ribs.<ref name=LATimes>{{cite news |title='I Am the Movies I Make': Martin Scorsese's passion and commitments earn him the AFI's most prestigious honor |first=Elaine |last=Dutka |url=https://articles.latimes.com/1997-02-22/entertainment/ca-31156_1_martin-scorsese |date=February 22, 1997 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=January 23, 2014 |quote=Joe Pesci testified to Scorsese's mania for realism. During a fight scene for ''Raging Bull'', he took such a beating from De Niro that he fell to the ground with a broken rib, he recalled. When a couple of 275-pound 'heifers' fell on him the wrong way in ''Casino'', that same rib was broken again. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221201646/http://articles.latimes.com/1997-02-22/entertainment/ca-31156_1_martin-scorsese |archive-date=February 21, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPesci won the [[BAFTA Film Award for Newcomer to Leading Film Roles]] in 1981 and was nominated for an Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor. Over the next few years, Pesci appeared in several smaller films, including ''[[Dear Mr. Wonderful]]'' (1982), ''[[Easy Money (1983 film)|Easy Money]]'' (1983) and ''[[Eureka (1983 film)|Eureka]]'' (1983).<ref name=\"yahoo\"/>\n\nIn 1984, he was cast in ''[[Once Upon a Time in America]]'', again appearing alongside De Niro. The following year he starred as private detective Rocky Nelson in the short-lived television comedy series ''[[Half Nelson (TV series)|Half Nelson]]''.<ref name=\"yahoo\" />\n\nIn 1988, Pesci appeared in the [[Michael Jackson]] musical anthology film ''[[Moonwalker]]'', in the film's sixth and longest segment, \"[[Smooth Criminal]].\" He played the antagonist, crime boss Frankie \"Mr. Big\" LiDeo (an anagram for one of the film's producers and longtime Jackson manager [[Frank DiLeo]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0095655/trivia |title=Moonwalker (1988) |work=IMDb |accessdate=October 21, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105145847/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0095655/trivia |archive-date=January 5, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> with whom Pesci later acted in ''Goodfellas'').<ref name=\"oscars1\" />\n\nHe appeared as Leo Getz, a comedic sidekick and best friend to protagonist detectives Martin Riggs ([[Mel Gibson]]) and Roger Murtaugh ([[Danny Glover]]) in the ''[[Lethal Weapon (film series)|Lethal Weapon]]'' sequels, released in 1989, 1992 and 1998.\n\nIn 1990, he reunited with Scorsese and De Niro for ''[[Goodfellas]]'', in which he played mobster Tommy DeVito, based on real-life mobster [[Thomas DeSimone]]. ([[Tommy DeVito (musician)|Tommy DeVito]] is also the name of Pesci's old acquaintance from Belleville, New Jersey, and a member of [[The Four Seasons (band)|The Four Seasons]], but contrary to popular belief, the naming is coincidental.<ref name=\"history vs hollywood\"/>) Pesci's old friend [[Frank Vincent]] also appears in the film; Pesci's character kills Vincent's character in a rage in one of the best-remembered scenes in the film after the Vincent character contemptuously tells him to \"go home and get your fucking shine box.\" According to Pesci, improvization and ad-libbing came out of rehearsals wherein Scorsese let the actors do whatever they wanted. He made transcripts of these sessions, took the lines the actors came up with that he liked best, and put them into a revised script that the cast worked from during principal photography.<ref name=Arnold>{{cite news |last=Arnold |first=Gary |title=Real Fellas Talk about Mob Film |work=[[The Washington Times]] |date=September 25, 1990}}</ref> For example, the scene where Tommy tells a story and Henry is responding to him\u2014the \"Funny how? Do I amuse you?\" scene\u2014is based on an actual event that Pesci experienced. Pesci was working as a waiter when he thought he was making a compliment to a mobster by saying he was \"funny\", however, the comment was not taken well.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/goodfellas-joe-pesci-funny-how-scene-2015-5?r=US&IR=T|title=One of the most famous scenes in 'Goodfellas' is based on something that actually happened to Joe Pesci|publisher=businessinsider.com|date=May 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Ultimate Book of Gangster Movies: Featuring the 100 Greatest Gangster Films of All Time|author1=George Anastasia|author2=Glen Macnow|publisher=Running Press|year=2011|ISBN= 9780762441549|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=kY5tHAksa7kC&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Ultimate+Book+of+Gangster+Movies:+Featuring+the+100+Greatest+Gangster+Films+of+All+Time&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwivn5yd04HnAhUBUt8KHbkeAGkQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=funny&f=false}}</ref> It was worked on in rehearsals where he and Liotta improvised, and Scorsese recorded four to five takes, rewrote their dialogue, and inserted it into the script.<ref name=Kaplan>{{cite video |people=Kaplan, Jonah (writer and editor); Stephen Altobellow and Jeffrey Schwartz (producers) |date=2004 |format=Blu-ray Disc |title=Getting Made: The Making of ''Goodfellas'' |work=Goodfellas |publisher=[[Warner Home Video]] |isbn=1-4198-4306-0}}</ref> The dinner scene with Tommy's mother was largely improvised.<ref name=Godfrey>{{cite web |last1=Godfrey |first1=Alex |title=Whaddya want from me? |url=http://mrgodfrey.tumblr.com/post/66620475687/whaddya-want-from-me |website=mrgodfrey |date=November 2013|access-date=August 22, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140904015411/http://mrgodfrey.tumblr.com/post/66620475687/whaddya-want-from-me|archive-date=September 4, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Pesci received the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]] for the role, which he accepted with one of the shortest speeches in Oscar history, saying simply, \"It's my privilege. Thank you\" before leaving the stage.<ref name=\"oscars1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1991/memorable-moments |title=The 63rd Academy Awards Memorable Moments |work=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences |year=2015 |accessdate=October 21, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151102095048/http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1991/memorable-moments |archive-date=November 2, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/55134/10-oscar-winners-whose-speeches-were-under-11-words |title=10 Oscar Winners Whose Speeches Were Under 11 Words |work=mental_floss |accessdate=February 13, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160214060824/http://mentalfloss.com/article/55134/10-oscar-winners-whose-speeches-were-under-11-words |archive-date=February 14, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPesci also co-starred in the blockbuster ''[[Home Alone]]'' in 1990, playing Harry Lyme, one of two bumbling burglars (along with good friend [[Daniel Stern (actor)|Daniel Stern]]) who attempt to burgle the house of the young character played by [[Macaulay Culkin]]. Pesci's use of \"cartoon cursing\", or menacing gibberish, garnered comparisons to ''[[Looney Tunes]]'' character [[Yosemite Sam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/archives/where-joe-pesci-saw-a-connection-between-looney-tunes-and-home-alone-1.4940775|title=Where Joe Pesci saw a connection between Looney Tunes and Home Alone|publisher=cbc.ca|date=December 11, 2019}}</ref> Two years later, Pesci reprised his role in the sequel ''[[Home Alone 2: Lost in New York]]''.\n\nIn 1991, Pesci played [[David Ferrie]] in ''[[JFK (film)|JFK]]''. In 1992 he appeared as the title character in the comedy ''[[My Cousin Vinny]]'' with [[Ralph Macchio]], [[Marisa Tomei]] and [[Fred Gwynne]]. The same year, Pesci spearheaded the cast of ''[[The Public Eye (film)|The Public Eye]]'' as Leon \"Bernzy\" Bernstein, a photographer. His performance in the film, a departure from his usual characters, was critically acclaimed.\n\nPesci hosted sketch comedy show ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' on October 10, 1992, while doing publicity for ''My Cousin Vinny''. During his monolog, he restored a picture of [[Pope John Paul II]] that had been torn by [[Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor]] on the previous broadcast.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/10/12/nyregion/chronicle-479092.html |title=CHRONICLE |last=Brozan |first=Nadine |date=October 12, 1992 |work=The New York Times|access-date=March 13, 2017 |issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313215234/http://www.nytimes.com/1992/10/12/nyregion/chronicle-479092.html|archive-date=March 13, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Pesci made an uncredited appearance in ''[[A Bronx Tale]]'' as Carmine. The film starred Robert De Niro, who also directed, and [[Chazz Palminteri]] who wrote the play from which the film was adapted. Both De Niro and Palminteri personally offered Pesci the role. In 1995, Pesci had his third collaboration with Scorsese and De Niro in the film ''[[Casino (1995 film)|Casino]]'', playing Nicky Santoro, based on real-life Mob enforcer [[Anthony Spilotro]], along with [[Sharon Stone]] and [[James Woods]]; Pesci had previously co-starred with the latter in ''Once Upon a Time in America''. During filming, Pesci broke the same rib that had been broken 15 years prior during the production of ''[[Raging Bull]]''.<ref name=LATimes/> In 1996, Pesci was considered to play Myron Larabee, the stressed-out postman, in ''[[Jingle All the Way]]'' opposite [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]], but the part was ultimately given to [[Sinbad (entertainer)|Sinbad]], whose physical size was more comparable to Schwarzenegger's.\n\nHe had starring roles in several other films, including ''[[Man on Fire (1987 film)|Man on Fire]]'' (1987), ''[[The Super (1991 film)|The Super]]'' (1991), ''[[Jimmy Hollywood]]'' (1994), ''[[With Honors (film)|With Honors]]'' (also 1994) and ''[[Gone Fishin' (film)|Gone Fishin']]'' (1997). Pesci's role in ''With Honors'' was a dramatic role in which he played a homeless man living on the campus of Harvard.\n\n=== Other work, retirement from acting and reprise for ''The Irishman'' ===\nIn 1998, he released his second album, and his first in 30 years, ''[[Vincent LaGuardia Gambini Sings Just for You]]'', which was named after his character from the 1992 film ''[[My Cousin Vinny]]''. The album was both humorous and serious, exploring a variety of genres, though most of it was [[big band]] [[jazz]]. The album spawned the single \"Wise Guy,\" a rap number that played on the [[gangsta rap|gangsta]] theme by making reference to [[American Mafia|Mafia]] gangsterism. \"Wise Guy\" interpolated the 1980 hit \"[[Rapture (Blondie song)|Rapture]]\" by [[Blondie (band)|Blondie]], and was co-written and produced by the hip-hop production team the [[Trackmasters]].\n\nIn 1999, Pesci announced his retirement from acting to pursue a musical career and to enjoy life away from the camera. He returned to acting when he did a [[cameo role|cameo]] in De Niro's 2006 film ''[[The Good Shepherd (film)|The Good Shepherd]]''. In 2010, he starred in the brothel drama ''[[Love Ranch]]'', alongside [[Helen Mirren]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.topnews.in/light/three-join-helen-mirren-and-joe-pesci-%E2%80%98love-ranch%E2%80%99-26500 |title=Three join Helen Mirren and Joe Pesci in 'Love Ranch' |publisher=Topnews.in |date=February 13, 2008 |accessdate=January 25, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110623205332/http://www.topnews.in/light/three-join-helen-mirren-and-joe-pesci-%E2%80%98love-ranch%E2%80%99-26500 |archive-date=June 23, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPesci appeared with [[Don Rickles]] in a 2011 [[Snickers]] advertisement in which he portrays the angry alter ego of a young man who attends a party and becomes agitated by two women until he is calmed down by eating a Snickers bar.<ref>{{cite web |title=There is an Angry Joe Pesci in all of us Snickers Ad |url=http://mememachine.viralvideochart.com/blog/2011/5/19/snickers-ad-there-is-an-angry-joe-pesci-in-all-of-us-just-in.html |work=mememachine |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613024651/http://mememachine.viralvideochart.com/blog/2011/5/19/snickers-ad-there-is-an-angry-joe-pesci-in-all-of-us-just-in.html |archivedate=June 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Pesci sued Fiore Films, the producers of the film ''[[Gotti (2018 film)|Gotti]]'', for having broken their promise to cast him in that film as real-life mobster [[Angelo Ruggiero]].<ref name=\"settles dispute\">{{cite web |title=Joe Pesci settles dispute over \"Gotti\" film payday |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/joe-pesci-settles-dispute-over-gotti-film-payday/ |publisher=CBS/AP |date=February 5, 2013 |access-date=January 9, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229112321/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/joe-pesci-settles-dispute-over-gotti-film-payday/ |archive-date=December 29, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>  Pesci stated that he had gained {{convert|30|lbs|kg}} for the role.<ref name=\"settles dispute\" /> He sued them for $3 million, which was the payment he had been promised.<ref name=\"settles dispute\" /> The lawsuit was settled out of court in 2013 for an unspecified sum,<ref name=\"settles dispute\" /> and the role, after many production delays, eventually went to [[Pruitt Taylor Vince]].\n\nPesci appears in the 2016 music documentary ''Jimmy Scott: I Go Back Home'' in which he is filmed recording \"[[The Folks Who Live on the Hill]]\" from Scott's 2017 posthumous album ''I Go Back Home''.\n\nIn 2017, Pesci was cast alongside [[Robert De Niro]] and [[Al Pacino]] in ''[[The Irishman]]'', a crime film directed by [[Martin Scorsese]]. Pesci was offered his role a reported 50 times before agreeing to take part, at first saying he did not want to do \"the gangster thing again\", while Scorsese tried to persuade him ''The Irishman'' would be \"different.\"<ref name=\"SpikeLee\">{{cite web |url=https://podcasts.apple.com/gb/podcast/the-irishman-with-martin-scorsese-and-spike-lee-episode-224/id1067471691?i=1000454929171 |title=The Irishman with Martin Scorsese and Spike Lee (Episode 224) |date=November 2019 |website=[[Apple Inc.]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191108152436/https://podcasts.apple.com/gb/podcast/the-irishman-with-martin-scorsese-and-spike-lee-episode-224/id1067471691?i=1000454929171 |archivedate=November 8, 2019 |accessdate=November 8, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The film received a [[limited theatrical release]] on November 1, 2019, followed by digital streaming on November 27, 2019 by [[Netflix]].<ref name=\"ReleaseDate\">{{cite web |first=Mike |last=Fleming Jr. |title=Netflix Sets November 1 Theatrical Bow For Martin Scorsese-Directed 'The Irishman:' 27 Day US & UK Rollout Comes Before Pic Streams For Thanksgiving Holiday |url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/the-irishman-netflix-november-1-theatrical-bow-martin-scorsese-robert-deniro-27-day-us-uk-rollout-stream-thanksgiving-holiday-1202704994/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827140928/https://deadline.com/2019/08/the-irishman-netflix-november-1-theatrical-bow-martin-scorsese-robert-deniro-27-day-us-uk-rollout-stream-thanksgiving-holiday-1202704994/ |website=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]] |date=August 27, 2019 |accessdate=September 19, 2019 |archivedate=August 27, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Pesci's performance as [[Russell Bufalino]] was critically acclaimed and earned him various accolades, including nominations for the [[92nd Academy Awards|Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/entertainment/2020/01/oscars-2020-joe-pesci-nominated-for-the-irishman-here-are-some-other-nj-ties.html|title=Oscars 2020: Joe Pesci nominated for 'The Irishman.' Here are some other N.J. ties.|last=NJ.com|first=Amy Kuperinsky {{!}} NJ Advance Media for|date=January 13, 2020|website=nj|language=en|access-date=January 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114155416/https://www.nj.com/entertainment/2020/01/oscars-2020-joe-pesci-nominated-for-the-irishman-here-are-some-other-nj-ties.html|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture|Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor]] and for two [[Screen Actors Guild Award]]s. Pesci also returned to music with his third album and his first in 21 years, titled ''Pesci... Still Singing'', released on November 29, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/joe-pesci-still-singing-review-album-adam-levine-jazz-a9223296.html|title=Joe Pesci's new jazz album is incredibly surreal, but sweet and sincere nonetheless \u2013 review|date=November 29, 2019|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=December 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191130141601/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/joe-pesci-still-singing-review-album-adam-levine-jazz-a9223296.html|archive-date=November 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Media depictions ==\nPesci is a character in the 2005 musical ''[[Jersey Boys]]'', which tells the story of [[The Four Seasons (band)|The Four Seasons]], due to his involvement in the band's formation. He is similarly a character in the musical's [[Jersey Boys (film)|2014 film adaptation]]. In the film, the Joe Pesci character asks \"Funny how?\", a quote from ''Goodfellas''.\n\nPesci was briefly a recurring character on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', played by [[Jim Breuer]]. Breuer's characterization was based on Pesci's ''GoodFellas'' character, re-imagined as a talk show host, but maintaining Tommy DeVito's violent temper, often beating his guests with a baseball bat. This recurring gag eventually culminated in the real Pesci appearing in a cameo and beating Breuer with a bat.\n\n== Personal life ==\nPesci has been married and divorced three times.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.philly.com/1992-03-14/news/26020215_1_cousin-vinny-vincent-la-guardia-gambini-identity-crisis |title=Now They're Good Fellas Ray Liotta And Joe Pesci Were Cold-blooded Wiseguys In Their 1990 Movie, But In Films Opening This Weekend, They're Unlikely Heroes. Joe Pesci Is Out For Justice |work=philly-archives |accessdate=October 21, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303223243/http://articles.philly.com/1992-03-14/news/26020215_1_cousin-vinny-vincent-la-guardia-gambini-identity-crisis |archive-date=March 3, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> His first marriage was in 1964.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/blogs/kats-report/2012/jun/04/pesci-remembers-his-own-honeymoon-vegas----meeting/ |title=Joe Pesci remembers his own honeymoon in Vegas -- meeting the Rat Pack |first=John |last=Katsilometes |work=Las Vegas Sun |accessdate=October 21, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105145848/http://lasvegassun.com/blogs/kats-report/2012/jun/04/pesci-remembers-his-own-honeymoon-vegas----meeting/ |archive-date=January 5, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> He fathered a daughter during his first marriage. His third marriage was from 1988 to 1992, to [[Claudia Haro]], a model and actress. In 2007, Pesci was engaged to [[Angie Everhart]],<ref name=sfgate>{{cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/blogs/sfgate/detail?blogid=7&entry_id=19023 |title=Pesci to Wed Everhart |accessdate=July 31, 2007 |date=July 30, 2007 |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |first=Karen |last=Reardanz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071021125937/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/blogs/sfgate/detail?blogid=7&entry_id=19023 |archive-date=October 21, 2007 |url-status=live}}</ref> but the couple broke up in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://breakingnews.iol.ie/entertainment/story.asp?j=253669330&p=z5367xx36 |title=Pesci ends engagement with model Everhart |accessdate=April 25, 2008 |date=April 25, 2008 |publisher=Ireland On-line |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430170839/http://breakingnews.iol.ie/entertainment/story.asp?j=253669330&p=z5367xx36 |archivedate=April 30, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1961\n| ''[[Hey, Let's Twist!]]''\n| Dancer at the Peppermint Lounge\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1976\n| ''[[The Death Collector]]''\n| Joe Salvino\n|\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[Raging Bull]]''\n|[[Joey LaMotta]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1982\n| ''[[I'm Dancing as Fast as I Can]]''\n| Roger\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Dear Mr. Wonderful]]''\n| Ruby Dennis\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1983\n| ''[[Eureka (1983 film)|Eureka]]''\n|Mayakofsky\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Easy Money (1983 film)|Easy Money]]''\n| Nicky Cerone\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1984\n| ''[[Once Upon a Time in America]]''\n| Frankie Minaldi\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Everybody in Jail]]''\n| Corrado Parisi\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[Man on Fire (1987 film)|Man on Fire]]''\n| David Coolidge\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1988\n| ''[[Moonwalker]]''\n| Frankie Lideo\n|\n|-\n| ''The Legendary Life of Ernest Hemingway''\n| [[John Dos Passos]]\n|\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Lethal Weapon 2]]''\n| Leo Getz\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=4 | 1990\n| ''[[Catchfire]]''\n| Leo Carelli\n| Uncredited cameo\n|-\n| ''[[Betsy's Wedding]]''\n| Oscar Henner\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Goodfellas]]''\n| [[Thomas DeSimone|Tommy DeVito]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Home Alone]]''\n| Harry Lyme\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1991\n| ''[[The Super (1991 film)|The Super]]''\n| Louie Kritski\n|\n|-\n| ''[[JFK (film)|JFK]]''\n| [[David Ferrie]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=4 | 1992\n| ''[[My Cousin Vinny]]''\n| Vincent LaGuardia Gambini\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Lethal Weapon 3]]''\n| Leo Getz\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Public Eye (film)|The Public Eye]]''\n| Leon Bernstein\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Home Alone 2: Lost in New York]]''\n| Harry Lyme\n|\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[A Bronx Tale]]''\n| Carmine\n| Uncredited cameo\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1994\n| ''[[Jimmy Hollywood]]''\n| Jimmy Alto\n|\n|-\n| ''[[With Honors (film)|With Honors]]''\n| Simon Wilder\n|\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Casino (1995 film)|Casino]]''\n| [[Anthony Spilotro|Nicky Santoro]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1997\n| ''[[8 Heads in a Duffel Bag]]''\n| Tommy Spinelli\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Gone Fishin' (film)|Gone Fishin']]''\n| Joe Waters\n|\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Lethal Weapon 4]]''\n| Leo Getz\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[The Good Shepherd (film)|The Good Shepherd]]''\n| Joseph Palmi\n| Cameo\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Love Ranch]]''\n| Charlie Bontempo\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[A Warrior's Tail]]''\n| Mosquito\n| Voice\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[The Irishman]]''\n| [[Russell Bufalino]]\n|\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Half Nelson (TV series)|Half Nelson]]''\n| Rocky Nelson\n| 6 episodes\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1992\n| ''[[Tales from the Crypt (TV series)|Tales from the Crypt]]''\n| Vic / Jack\n| Episode: \"[[List of Tales from the Crypt episodes#Season 4 (1992)|Split Personality]]\"\n|-\n| ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''\n| Himself / Host\n| Episode: \"[[Saturday Night Live (season 18)#ep329|Joe Pesci/The Spin Doctors]]\"\n|}\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Joe Pesci}}\n\n== Discography ==\n* ''Little Joe Sure Can Sing!'' (1968) (Brunswick Records)\n* ''[[Vincent LaGuardia Gambini Sings Just for You]]'' (1998) (Columbia Records)\n* ''Pesci... Still Singing'' (2019) (BMG Rights Management)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name}}\n* {{TCMDb name}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Joe Pesci|Awards for Joe Pesci]]\n|list =\n{{Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor}}\n{{Bafta Award for Most Promising Newcomer}}\n{{Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Supporting Actor}}\n{{London Film Critics Circle Award for Supporting Actor of the Year}}\n{{Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Supporting Actor}}\n{{National Board of Review Award for Best Supporting Actor}}\n{{National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Supporting Actor}}\n{{New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Supporting Actor}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pesci, Joe}}\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (people)]]\n[[Category:Belleville High School (New Jersey) alumni]]\n[[Category:Best Supporting Actor Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Newark, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Male actors of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Newark, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Belleville, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Newark, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Ocean County, New Jersey]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc}}\n{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Joe Pesci\n| image              = JoePesci-2009.jpg\n| alt                = A head shot of Pesci, unshaven, wearing dark sunglasses, hat, shirt, and leather jacket\n| caption            = Pesci in November 2009\n| birth_name         = Joseph Frank Pesci\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1943|2|9}}  \n| birth_place        = [[Newark, New Jersey]], U.S.\n| residence          = [[Lavallette, New Jersey]], U.S.\n| occupation         = Actor, musician<!--Please do not add \"comedian\" as it was for a very brief period early on in his career, which is not something he is known for.-->\n| years_active       = 1961\u20131999; 2006\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Claudia Haro]]|1988|1992|reason=divorced}}\n| partner            = [[Angie Everhart]] (2000\u20132008)\n| children           = 1\n}}\n\n'''Joseph Frank Pesci''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|p|\u025b|\u0283|i}} {{respell|PESH|ee}}, {{IPA-it|\u02c8pe\u0283\u02d0i}}; born February 9, 1943) is an American actor and musician<!--Please do not add \"comedian\" as it was for a very brief period early on in his career, which is not something he is known for.-->. He is known for portraying tough, volatile characters in a variety of genres and for his collaborations with [[Robert De Niro]] and [[Martin Scorsese]] in the films ''[[Raging Bull]]'' (1980), ''[[Goodfellas]]'' (1990), ''[[Casino (1995 film)|Casino]]'' (1995), and ''[[The Irishman]]'' (2019). He also appeared in ''[[Once Upon a Time in America]]'' (1984), ''[[Moonwalker]]'' (1988), ''[[JFK (film)|JFK]]'' (1991), ''[[A Bronx Tale]]'' (1993), and ''[[The Good Shepherd (film)|The Good Shepherd]]'' (2006). His comedy roles include such films as ''[[Home Alone]]'' (1990), ''[[My Cousin Vinny]]'' (1992), ''[[Home Alone 2: Lost in New York]]'' (1992), and the [[Lethal Weapon (franchise)|''Lethal Weapon'' franchise]] (1989\u20131998).\n\nPesci won the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]] for his role as the psychopathic gangster [[Thomas DeSimone|Tommy DeVito]] in ''Goodfellas'' and received two other nominations in the same category for his portrayals of [[Joey LaMotta]] and [[Russell Bufalino]] in 1980's ''Raging Bull'' and in 2019's ''The Irishman'', respectively. He announced his retirement from acting in 1999, and has since appeared only occasionally in films. He is also a musician who recorded three studio albums, ''Little Joe Sure Can Sing!'' (1968), ''[[Vincent LaGuardia Gambini Sings Just for You]]'' (1998) and ''Pesci... Still Singing'' (2019).\n\n== Early life ==\nPesci was born on February 9, 1943, in [[Newark, New Jersey]]. His mother, Maria (Mesce), worked part-time as a barber, and his father, Angelo Pesci, was a [[forklift]] driver for [[General Motors]] and a bartender. He is of Italian descent, with origins in [[Turin]]<ref name=\"character\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/03/08/movies/film-joe-pesci-that-guy-is-some-kind-of-character.html |title=Joe Pesci? That Guy Is Some Kind of Character |first=Nancy |last=Harrison |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 8, 1992 |publisher=[[New York Times Company|NYTC]] |location=[[New York, NY|New York]] |issn=0362-4331 |accessdate=October 21, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151114195953/http://www.nytimes.com/1992/03/08/movies/film-joe-pesci-that-guy-is-some-kind-of-character.html |archive-date=November 14, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://celebritywonder.ugo.com/html/joepesci.html |title=Joe Pesci |work=celebritywonder |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110321114922/http://celebritywonder.ugo.com/html/joepesci.html |archivedate=March 21, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=MHJ1DQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=%22Italian+Americans:+The+History+and+Culture+of+a+People%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjS37SP-MjmAhXDK80KHd3VChIQ6AEwAHoECAAQAQ|title=Italian Americans: The History and Culture of a People|first=Eric|last=Martone|date=December 12, 2016|publisher=ABC-CLIO|via=Google Books}}</ref> and [[Aquilonia, Campania|Aquilonia]] in [[province of Avellino]].<ref>{{cite news |last1= Aspesi|first1=Natalia|author-link1= |last2= |first2= |author-link2= |last3= |first3= |author-link3= |last4= |first4= |author-link4= |last5= |first5= |author-link5= |display-authors= |author-mask= |name-list-format= |last-author-amp= |date= |year= |orig-year= |title=Piccolo e nero mezzo italiano Pesci \u00e8 la star |script-title= |trans-title= |url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/1992/09/04/piccolo-nero-mezzo-italiano-pesci-la.html |url-status= |editor1-last= |editor1-first= |editor1-link= |editor2-last= |editor2-first= |editor2-link= |editor3-last= |editor3-first= |editor3-link= |editor4-last= |editor4-first= |editor4-link= |editor5-last= |editor5-first= |editor5-link= |display-editors= |department= |work=la Repubblica |type= |series= |language=Italian |volume= |issue= |others= |edition= |location= Rome|publisher=GEDI Gruppo Editoriale |publication-date=September 4, 1992 |agency= |page= |pages= |at= |nopp= |arxiv= |asin= |bibcode= |doi= |doi-broken-date= |isbn= |issn= |jfm= |jstor= |lccn= |mr= |oclc= |ol= |osti= |pmc= |pmid= |rfc= |ssrn= |zbl= |id= |archive-url= |archive-date= |access-date=February 9, 2020 |via= |registration= |lay-url= |lay-source= |lay-date= |quote= |postscript= |ref= }}</ref> Pesci was raised in [[Belleville, New Jersey]], and graduated from [[Belleville High School (New Jersey)|Belleville High School]]. By the time Pesci was five years old, he was appearing in plays in New York.<ref name=\"character\" /> At age 10, he was a regular on a television variety show called ''Startime Kids'', which also featured [[Connie Francis]].<ref name=\"character\" />\n\nAs a teenager, Pesci was friends with singers [[Frankie Valli]] (who is nine years his senior) and [[Tommy DeVito (musician)|Tommy DeVito]] (who is 15 years his senior), and in 1959, at age 16, he helped introduce them to singer and songwriter [[Bob Gaudio]], which led to the formation of the band [[The Four Seasons (band)|the Four Seasons]].<ref name=\"history vs hollywood\">{{cite web |url=http://www.historyvshollywood.com/reelfaces/jersey-boys/ |title=Jersey Boys Movie vs True Story \u2013 Real Frankie Valli, Tommy DeVito |work=HistoryvsHollywood.com |accessdate=October 21, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150627204444/http://www.historyvshollywood.com/reelfaces/jersey-boys/ |archivedate=June 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n=== Early career ===\nIn the 1960s, Pesci began working as a barber, following in his mother's footsteps. At the same time, he tried to start a musical career, playing guitar with several bands, including [[Joey Dee and the Starliters]] who introduced the \"[[Peppermint Twist]]\" record, dance, and Peppermint Lounge in New York City.\n\nIn 1968, he released his debut album ''Little Joe Sure Can Sing!'' (billed as ''Joe Ritchie''), on which he sang covers of contemporary pop hits.<ref name=\"yahoo\">{{cite web |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/person/joe-pesci/biography.html |title=Joe Pesci biography |work=[[Yahoo! Movies]] |access-date=January 14, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315102847/https://movies.yahoo.com/person/joe-pesci/biography.html |archive-date=March 15, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPesci later joined [[Frank Vincent]] as a [[comedy duo]], performing as \"Vincent and Pesci\" from 1970 to 1976. Their act coupled [[Abbott and Costello]]-inspired double act antics with [[Don Rickles]]-style [[insult comedy]], which proved popular with crowds. During this time, both men developed a strong professional and personal friendship with one another.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lewine |first1=Edward |title=Frank Vincent's Two-Limo Night |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/18/nyregion/frank-vincent-s-two-limo-night.html |website=[[New York Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Eidelstein |first1=Eric |title=The Mysterious Disappearing Act of Joe Pesci |url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2015/09/where-are-you-joe-pesci |website=[[Complex (magazine)]]}}</ref> In 1975, they appeared in the Broadway show ''The New Vaudevillians'', which only lasted one week.<ref name=\"yahoo\" />\n\nThe first film Pesci starred in was the 1976 [[Low-budget film|low-budget]] [[crime film]] ''[[The Death Collector]]'' alongside Frank Vincent. After the film Pesci returned to The Bronx and lived above Amici's Restaurant, where he was an employee.<ref name=\"yahoo\" />\n\n=== Acting career ===\nIn 1979, Pesci received a telephone call from [[Martin Scorsese]] and Robert De Niro, who were impressed with his performance in ''The Death Collector'' and asked him to co-star in Scorsese's ''[[Raging Bull]]'' as [[Joey LaMotta]]. During the course of filming, Pesci broke one of his ribs.<ref name=LATimes>{{cite news |title='I Am the Movies I Make': Martin Scorsese's passion and commitments earn him the AFI's most prestigious honor |first=Elaine |last=Dutka |url=https://articles.latimes.com/1997-02-22/entertainment/ca-31156_1_martin-scorsese |date=February 22, 1997 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=January 23, 2014 |quote=Joe Pesci testified to Scorsese's mania for realism. During a fight scene for ''Raging Bull'', he took such a beating from De Niro that he fell to the ground with a broken rib, he recalled. When a couple of 275-pound 'heifers' fell on him the wrong way in ''Casino'', that same rib was broken again. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221201646/http://articles.latimes.com/1997-02-22/entertainment/ca-31156_1_martin-scorsese |archive-date=February 21, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPesci won the [[BAFTA Film Award for Newcomer to Leading Film Roles]] in 1981 and was nominated for an Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor. Over the next few years, Pesci appeared in several smaller films, including ''[[Dear Mr. Wonderful]]'' (1982), ''[[Easy Money (1983 film)|Easy Money]]'' (1983) and ''[[Eureka (1983 film)|Eureka]]'' (1983).<ref name=\"yahoo\"/>\n\nIn 1984, he was cast in ''[[Once Upon a Time in America]]'', again appearing alongside De Niro. The following year he starred as private detective Rocky Nelson in the short-lived television comedy series ''[[Half Nelson (TV series)|Half Nelson]]''.<ref name=\"yahoo\" />\n\nIn 1988, Pesci appeared in the [[Michael Jackson]] musical anthology film ''[[Moonwalker]]'', in the film's sixth and longest segment, \"[[Smooth Criminal]].\" He played the antagonist, crime boss Frankie \"Mr. Big\" LiDeo (an anagram for one of the film's producers and longtime Jackson manager [[Frank DiLeo]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0095655/trivia |title=Moonwalker (1988) |work=IMDb |accessdate=October 21, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105145847/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0095655/trivia |archive-date=January 5, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> with whom Pesci later acted in ''Goodfellas'').<ref name=\"oscars1\" />\n\nHe appeared as Leo Getz, a comedic sidekick and best friend to protagonist detectives Martin Riggs ([[Mel Gibson]]) and Roger Murtaugh ([[Danny Glover]]) in the ''[[Lethal Weapon (film series)|Lethal Weapon]]'' sequels, released in 1989, 1992 and 1998.\n\nIn 1990, he reunited with Scorsese and De Niro for ''[[Goodfellas]]'', in which he played mobster Tommy DeVito, based on real-life mobster [[Thomas DeSimone]]. ([[Tommy DeVito (musician)|Tommy DeVito]] is also the name of Pesci's old acquaintance from Belleville, New Jersey, and a member of [[The Four Seasons (band)|The Four Seasons]], but contrary to popular belief, the naming is coincidental.<ref name=\"history vs hollywood\"/>) Pesci's old friend [[Frank Vincent]] also appears in the film; Pesci's character kills Vincent's character in a rage in one of the best-remembered scenes in the film after the Vincent character contemptuously tells him to \"go home and get your fucking shine box.\" According to Pesci, improvization and ad-libbing came out of rehearsals wherein Scorsese let the actors do whatever they wanted. He made transcripts of these sessions, took the lines the actors came up with that he liked best, and put them into a revised script that the cast worked from during principal photography.<ref name=Arnold>{{cite news |last=Arnold |first=Gary |title=Real Fellas Talk about Mob Film |work=[[The Washington Times]] |date=September 25, 1990}}</ref> For example, the scene where Tommy tells a story and Henry is responding to him\u2014the \"Funny how? Do I amuse you?\" scene\u2014is based on an actual event that Pesci experienced. Pesci was working as a waiter when he thought he was making a compliment to a mobster by saying he was \"funny\", however, the comment was not taken well.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/goodfellas-joe-pesci-funny-how-scene-2015-5?r=US&IR=T|title=One of the most famous scenes in 'Goodfellas' is based on something that actually happened to Joe Pesci|publisher=businessinsider.com|date=May 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Ultimate Book of Gangster Movies: Featuring the 100 Greatest Gangster Films of All Time|author1=George Anastasia|author2=Glen Macnow|publisher=Running Press|year=2011|ISBN= 9780762441549|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=kY5tHAksa7kC&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Ultimate+Book+of+Gangster+Movies:+Featuring+the+100+Greatest+Gangster+Films+of+All+Time&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwivn5yd04HnAhUBUt8KHbkeAGkQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=funny&f=false}}</ref> It was worked on in rehearsals where he and Liotta improvised, and Scorsese recorded four to five takes, rewrote their dialogue, and inserted it into the script.<ref name=Kaplan>{{cite video |people=Kaplan, Jonah (writer and editor); Stephen Altobellow and Jeffrey Schwartz (producers) |date=2004 |format=Blu-ray Disc |title=Getting Made: The Making of ''Goodfellas'' |work=Goodfellas |publisher=[[Warner Home Video]] |isbn=1-4198-4306-0}}</ref> The dinner scene with Tommy's mother was largely improvised.<ref name=Godfrey>{{cite web |last1=Godfrey |first1=Alex |title=Whaddya want from me? |url=http://mrgodfrey.tumblr.com/post/66620475687/whaddya-want-from-me |website=mrgodfrey |date=November 2013|access-date=August 22, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140904015411/http://mrgodfrey.tumblr.com/post/66620475687/whaddya-want-from-me|archive-date=September 4, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Pesci received the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]] for the role, which he accepted with one of the shortest speeches in Oscar history, saying simply, \"It's my privilege. Thank you\" before leaving the stage.<ref name=\"oscars1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1991/memorable-moments |title=The 63rd Academy Awards Memorable Moments |work=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences |year=2015 |accessdate=October 21, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151102095048/http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1991/memorable-moments |archive-date=November 2, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/55134/10-oscar-winners-whose-speeches-were-under-11-words |title=10 Oscar Winners Whose Speeches Were Under 11 Words |work=mental_floss |accessdate=February 13, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160214060824/http://mentalfloss.com/article/55134/10-oscar-winners-whose-speeches-were-under-11-words |archive-date=February 14, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPesci also co-starred in the blockbuster ''[[Home Alone]]'' in 1990, playing Harry Lyme, one of two bumbling burglars (along with good friend [[Daniel Stern (actor)|Daniel Stern]]) who attempt to burgle the house of the young character played by [[Macaulay Culkin]]. Pesci's use of \"cartoon cursing\", or menacing gibberish, garnered comparisons to ''[[Looney Tunes]]'' character [[Yosemite Sam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/archives/where-joe-pesci-saw-a-connection-between-looney-tunes-and-home-alone-1.4940775|title=Where Joe Pesci saw a connection between Looney Tunes and Home Alone|publisher=cbc.ca|date=December 11, 2019}}</ref> Two years later, Pesci reprised his role in the sequel ''[[Home Alone 2: Lost in New York]]''.\n\nIn 1991, Pesci played [[David Ferrie]] in ''[[JFK (film)|JFK]]''. In 1992 he appeared as the title character in the comedy ''[[My Cousin Vinny]]'' with [[Ralph Macchio]], [[Marisa Tomei]] and [[Fred Gwynne]]. The same year, Pesci spearheaded the cast of ''[[The Public Eye (film)|The Public Eye]]'' as Leon \"Bernzy\" Bernstein, a photographer. His performance in the film, a departure from his usual characters, was critically acclaimed.\n\nPesci hosted sketch comedy show ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' on October 10, 1992, while doing publicity for ''My Cousin Vinny''. During his monolog, he restored a picture of [[Pope John Paul II]] that had been torn by [[Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor]] on the previous broadcast.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/10/12/nyregion/chronicle-479092.html |title=CHRONICLE |last=Brozan |first=Nadine |date=October 12, 1992 |work=The New York Times|access-date=March 13, 2017 |issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313215234/http://www.nytimes.com/1992/10/12/nyregion/chronicle-479092.html|archive-date=March 13, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Pesci made an uncredited appearance in ''[[A Bronx Tale]]'' as Carmine. The film starred Robert De Niro, who also directed, and [[Chazz Palminteri]] who wrote the play from which the film was adapted. Both De Niro and Palminteri personally offered Pesci the role. In 1995, Pesci had his third collaboration with Scorsese and De Niro in the film ''[[Casino (1995 film)|Casino]]'', playing Nicky Santoro, based on real-life Mob enforcer [[Anthony Spilotro]], along with [[Sharon Stone]] and [[James Woods]]; Pesci had previously co-starred with the latter in ''Once Upon a Time in America''. During filming, Pesci broke the same rib that had been broken 15 years prior during the production of ''[[Raging Bull]]''.<ref name=LATimes/> In 1996, Pesci was considered to play Myron Larabee, the stressed-out postman, in ''[[Jingle All the Way]]'' opposite [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]], but the part was ultimately given to [[Sinbad (entertainer)|Sinbad]], whose physical size was more comparable to Schwarzenegger's.\n\nHe had starring roles in several other films, including ''[[Man on Fire (1987 film)|Man on Fire]]'' (1987), ''[[The Super (1991 film)|The Super]]'' (1991), ''[[Jimmy Hollywood]]'' (1994), ''[[With Honors (film)|With Honors]]'' (also 1994) and ''[[Gone Fishin' (film)|Gone Fishin']]'' (1997). Pesci's role in ''With Honors'' was a dramatic role in which he played a homeless man living on the campus of Harvard.\n\n=== Other work, retirement from acting and reprise for ''The Irishman'' ===\nIn 1998, he released his second album, and his first in 30 years, ''[[Vincent LaGuardia Gambini Sings Just for You]]'', which was named after his character from the 1992 film ''[[My Cousin Vinny]]''. The album was both humorous and serious, exploring a variety of genres, though most of it was [[big band]] [[jazz]]. The album spawned the single \"Wise Guy,\" a rap number that played on the [[gangsta rap|gangsta]] theme by making reference to [[American Mafia|Mafia]] gangsterism. \"Wise Guy\" interpolated the 1980 hit \"[[Rapture (Blondie song)|Rapture]]\" by [[Blondie (band)|Blondie]], and was co-written and produced by the hip-hop production team the [[Trackmasters]].\n\nIn 1999, Pesci announced his retirement from acting to pursue a musical career and to enjoy life away from the camera. He returned to acting when he did a [[cameo role|cameo]] in De Niro's 2006 film ''[[The Good Shepherd (film)|The Good Shepherd]]''. In 2010, he starred in the brothel drama ''[[Love Ranch]]'', alongside [[Helen Mirren]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.topnews.in/light/three-join-helen-mirren-and-joe-pesci-%E2%80%98love-ranch%E2%80%99-26500 |title=Three join Helen Mirren and Joe Pesci in 'Love Ranch' |publisher=Topnews.in |date=February 13, 2008 |accessdate=January 25, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110623205332/http://www.topnews.in/light/three-join-helen-mirren-and-joe-pesci-%E2%80%98love-ranch%E2%80%99-26500 |archive-date=June 23, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPesci appeared with [[Don Rickles]] in a 2011 [[Snickers]] advertisement in which he portrays the angry alter ego of a young man who attends a party and becomes agitated by two women until he is calmed down by eating a Snickers bar.<ref>{{cite web |title=There is an Angry Joe Pesci in all of us Snickers Ad |url=http://mememachine.viralvideochart.com/blog/2011/5/19/snickers-ad-there-is-an-angry-joe-pesci-in-all-of-us-just-in.html |work=mememachine |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613024651/http://mememachine.viralvideochart.com/blog/2011/5/19/snickers-ad-there-is-an-angry-joe-pesci-in-all-of-us-just-in.html |archivedate=June 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Pesci sued Fiore Films, the producers of the film ''[[Gotti (2018 film)|Gotti]]'', for having broken their promise to cast him in that film as real-life mobster [[Angelo Ruggiero]].<ref name=\"settles dispute\">{{cite web |title=Joe Pesci settles dispute over \"Gotti\" film payday |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/joe-pesci-settles-dispute-over-gotti-film-payday/ |publisher=CBS/AP |date=February 5, 2013 |access-date=January 9, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229112321/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/joe-pesci-settles-dispute-over-gotti-film-payday/ |archive-date=December 29, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>  Pesci stated that he had gained {{convert|30|lbs|kg}} for the role.<ref name=\"settles dispute\" /> He sued them for $3 million, which was the payment he had been promised.<ref name=\"settles dispute\" /> The lawsuit was settled out of court in 2013 for an unspecified sum,<ref name=\"settles dispute\" /> and the role, after many production delays, eventually went to [[Pruitt Taylor Vince]].\n\nPesci appears in the 2016 music documentary ''Jimmy Scott: I Go Back Home'' in which he is filmed recording \"[[The Folks Who Live on the Hill]]\" from Scott's 2017 posthumous album ''I Go Back Home''.\n\nIn 2017, Pesci was cast alongside [[Robert De Niro]] and [[Al Pacino]] in ''[[The Irishman]]'', a crime film directed by [[Martin Scorsese]]. Pesci was offered his role a reported 50 times before agreeing to take part, at first saying he did not want to do \"the gangster thing again\", while Scorsese tried to persuade him ''The Irishman'' would be \"different.\"<ref name=\"SpikeLee\">{{cite web |url=https://podcasts.apple.com/gb/podcast/the-irishman-with-martin-scorsese-and-spike-lee-episode-224/id1067471691?i=1000454929171 |title=The Irishman with Martin Scorsese and Spike Lee (Episode 224) |date=November 2019 |website=[[Apple Inc.]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191108152436/https://podcasts.apple.com/gb/podcast/the-irishman-with-martin-scorsese-and-spike-lee-episode-224/id1067471691?i=1000454929171 |archivedate=November 8, 2019 |accessdate=November 8, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The film received a [[limited theatrical release]] on November 1, 2019, followed by digital streaming on November 27, 2019 by [[Netflix]].<ref name=\"ReleaseDate\">{{cite web |first=Mike |last=Fleming Jr. |title=Netflix Sets November 1 Theatrical Bow For Martin Scorsese-Directed 'The Irishman:' 27 Day US & UK Rollout Comes Before Pic Streams For Thanksgiving Holiday |url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/the-irishman-netflix-november-1-theatrical-bow-martin-scorsese-robert-deniro-27-day-us-uk-rollout-stream-thanksgiving-holiday-1202704994/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827140928/https://deadline.com/2019/08/the-irishman-netflix-november-1-theatrical-bow-martin-scorsese-robert-deniro-27-day-us-uk-rollout-stream-thanksgiving-holiday-1202704994/ |website=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]] |date=August 27, 2019 |accessdate=September 19, 2019 |archivedate=August 27, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Pesci's performance as [[Russell Bufalino]] was critically acclaimed and earned him various accolades, including nominations for the [[92nd Academy Awards|Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/entertainment/2020/01/oscars-2020-joe-pesci-nominated-for-the-irishman-here-are-some-other-nj-ties.html|title=Oscars 2020: Joe Pesci nominated for 'The Irishman.' Here are some other N.J. ties.|last=NJ.com|first=Amy Kuperinsky {{!}} NJ Advance Media for|date=January 13, 2020|website=nj|language=en|access-date=January 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114155416/https://www.nj.com/entertainment/2020/01/oscars-2020-joe-pesci-nominated-for-the-irishman-here-are-some-other-nj-ties.html|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture|Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor]] and for two [[Screen Actors Guild Award]]s. Pesci also returned to music with his third album and his first in 21 years, titled ''Pesci... Still Singing'', released on November 29, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/joe-pesci-still-singing-review-album-adam-levine-jazz-a9223296.html|title=Joe Pesci's new jazz album is incredibly surreal, but sweet and sincere nonetheless \u2013 review|date=November 29, 2019|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=December 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191130141601/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/joe-pesci-still-singing-review-album-adam-levine-jazz-a9223296.html|archive-date=November 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Media depictions ==\nPesci is a character in the 2005 musical ''[[Jersey Boys]]'', which tells the story of [[The Four Seasons (band)|The Four Seasons]], due to his involvement in the band's formation. He is similarly a character in the musical's [[Jersey Boys (film)|2014 film adaptation]]. In the film, the Joe Pesci character asks \"Funny how?\", a quote from ''Goodfellas''.\n\nPesci was briefly a recurring character on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', played by [[Jim Breuer]]. Breuer's characterization was based on Pesci's ''GoodFellas'' character, re-imagined as a talk show host, but maintaining Tommy DeVito's violent temper, often beating his guests with a baseball bat. This recurring gag eventually culminated in the real Pesci appearing in a cameo and beating Breuer with a bat.\n\n== Personal life ==\nPesci has been married and divorced three times.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.philly.com/1992-03-14/news/26020215_1_cousin-vinny-vincent-la-guardia-gambini-identity-crisis |title=Now They're Good Fellas Ray Liotta And Joe Pesci Were Cold-blooded Wiseguys In Their 1990 Movie, But In Films Opening This Weekend, They're Unlikely Heroes. Joe Pesci Is Out For Justice |work=philly-archives |accessdate=October 21, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303223243/http://articles.philly.com/1992-03-14/news/26020215_1_cousin-vinny-vincent-la-guardia-gambini-identity-crisis |archive-date=March 3, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> His first marriage was in 1964.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/blogs/kats-report/2012/jun/04/pesci-remembers-his-own-honeymoon-vegas----meeting/ |title=Joe Pesci remembers his own honeymoon in Vegas -- meeting the Rat Pack |first=John |last=Katsilometes |work=Las Vegas Sun |accessdate=October 21, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105145848/http://lasvegassun.com/blogs/kats-report/2012/jun/04/pesci-remembers-his-own-honeymoon-vegas----meeting/ |archive-date=January 5, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> He fathered a daughter during his first marriage. His third marriage was from 1988 to 1992, to [[Claudia Haro]], a model and actress. In 2007, Pesci was engaged to [[Angie Everhart]],<ref name=sfgate>{{cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/blogs/sfgate/detail?blogid=7&entry_id=19023 |title=Pesci to Wed Everhart |accessdate=July 31, 2007 |date=July 30, 2007 |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |first=Karen |last=Reardanz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071021125937/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/blogs/sfgate/detail?blogid=7&entry_id=19023 |archive-date=October 21, 2007 |url-status=live}}</ref> but the couple broke up in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://breakingnews.iol.ie/entertainment/story.asp?j=253669330&p=z5367xx36 |title=Pesci ends engagement with model Everhart |accessdate=April 25, 2008 |date=April 25, 2008 |publisher=Ireland On-line |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430170839/http://breakingnews.iol.ie/entertainment/story.asp?j=253669330&p=z5367xx36 |archivedate=April 30, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1961\n| ''[[Hey, Let's Twist!]]''\n| Dancer at the Peppermint Lounge\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1976\n| ''[[The Death Collector]]''\n| Joe Salvino\n|\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[Raging Bull]]''\n|[[Joey LaMotta]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1982\n| ''[[I'm Dancing as Fast as I Can]]''\n| Roger\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Dear Mr. Wonderful]]''\n| Ruby Dennis\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1983\n| ''[[Eureka (1983 film)|Eureka]]''\n|Mayakofsky\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Easy Money (1983 film)|Easy Money]]''\n| Nicky Cerone\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1984\n| ''[[Once Upon a Time in America]]''\n| Frankie Minaldi\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Everybody in Jail]]''\n| Corrado Parisi\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[Man on Fire (1987 film)|Man on Fire]]''\n| David Coolidge\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1988\n| ''[[Moonwalker]]''\n| Frankie Lideo\n|\n|-\n| ''The Legendary Life of Ernest Hemingway''\n| [[John Dos Passos]]\n|\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Lethal Weapon 2]]''\n| Leo Getz\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=4 | 1990\n| ''[[Catchfire]]''\n| Leo Carelli\n| Uncredited cameo\n|-\n| ''[[Betsy's Wedding]]''\n| Oscar Henner\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Goodfellas]]''\n| [[Thomas DeSimone|Tommy DeVito]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Home Alone]]''\n| Harry Lyme\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1991\n| ''[[The Super (1991 film)|The Super]]''\n| Louie Kritski\n|\n|-\n| ''[[JFK (film)|JFK]]''\n| [[David Ferrie]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=4 | 1992\n| ''[[My Cousin Vinny]]''\n| Vincent LaGuardia Gambini\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Lethal Weapon 3]]''\n| Leo Getz\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Public Eye (film)|The Public Eye]]''\n| Leon Bernstein\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Home Alone 2: Lost in New York]]''\n| Harry Lyme\n|\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[A Bronx Tale]]''\n| Carmine\n| Uncredited cameo\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1994\n| ''[[Jimmy Hollywood]]''\n| Jimmy Alto\n|\n|-\n| ''[[With Honors (film)|With Honors]]''\n| Simon Wilder\n|\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Casino (1995 film)|Casino]]''\n| [[Anthony Spilotro|Nicky Santoro]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1997\n| ''[[8 Heads in a Duffel Bag]]''\n| Tommy Spinelli\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Gone Fishin' (film)|Gone Fishin']]''\n| Joe Waters\n|\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Lethal Weapon 4]]''\n| Leo Getz\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[The Good Shepherd (film)|The Good Shepherd]]''\n| Joseph Palmi\n| Cameo\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Love Ranch]]''\n| Charlie Bontempo\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[A Warrior's Tail]]''\n| Mosquito\n| Voice\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[The Irishman]]''\n| [[Russell Bufalino]]\n|\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Half Nelson (TV series)|Half Nelson]]''\n| Rocky Nelson\n| 6 episodes\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1992\n| ''[[Tales from the Crypt (TV series)|Tales from the Crypt]]''\n| Vic / Jack\n| Episode: \"[[List of Tales from the Crypt episodes#Season 4 (1992)|Split Personality]]\"\n|-\n| ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''\n| Himself / Host\n| Episode: \"[[Saturday Night Live (season 18)#ep329|Joe Pesci/The Spin Doctors]]\"\n|}\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Joe Pesci}}\n\n== Discography ==\n* ''Little Joe Sure Can Sing!'